  "issue_number": 1806,
  "issue_title": "Missing test coverage from pull request #1511?",
  "issue_body": "As part of pull request #1511, the changes may have fixed a bug related to native type rendering for iterator; it could be worth adding test coverage related to that.\r\n\r\nBefore #1511, the code was calling `itertools.islice(values, 2)` to retrieve the head elements from a `values` collection (potentially of an iterator type) and then using `itertools.chain(head, values)` to subsequently produce output.\r\n\r\nIn the case where `values` _is_ an iterator, I think that works correctly.  But in cases where `values` is _not_ an iterator, it can result in output duplication (something that I think #1511 indirectly resolves with [this check](https://github.com/pallets/jinja/pull/1511/commits/2903565262e6c8971e612a2717feb430e284e4ac#diff-25a3ba2093b8517416a58a44407a2580496610a92a90b6d6550da54ce4f3220cR35-R37)).\r\n\r\nFor example:\r\n\r\n```pycon\r\n>>> from itertools import islice\r\n>>> values = [1,2,3,4]\r\n>>> head = islice(values, 2)\r\n>>> from itertools import chain\r\n>>> list(chain(head, values))\r\n[1, 2, 1, 2, 3, 4]\r\n```",
  "merged_at": "2024-07-10T16:14:52Z",
